  "reference": {
    "pmid": "12771613",
    "doi": null,
    "title": "Beneficial hemodynamic and renal effects of intravenous enalaprilat following coronary artery bypass surgery complicated by left ventricular dysfunction.",
    "abstract": "Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors are an effective therapy for all stages of heart failure due to reduced systolic left ventricular function. Because sufficient data on intravenous angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors following coronary artery bypass surgery complicated by postoperative left ventricular dysfunction are unavailable, the efficacy and safety of intravenously administered enalaprilat were evaluated.",
    "journal": "Critical care medicine",
    "date": "2003-06-16",
    "authors": [
      "Frank Wagner",
      "Ruhi Yeter",
      "Susanne Bisson",
      "Henryk Siniawski",
      "Roland Hetzer"
    ]
  },
  "curators": [
    "Shubhankar Palwankar"
  ],
  "descriptions": [
    "Forty patients (eight female, 32 male) with a mean age of 60 ± 8 yrs (range, 43–77 yrs) were included in the study",
    "the infusion pump was started at a rate of 0.625 mg/hr at a concentration of 0.025 mg/mL enalaprilat in 0.9% NaCl or placebo.",
    "After 1 hr, if no adverse events occurred, the infusion pump was changed to a constant infusion of 0.1 mg/mL concentration of enalaprilat infused at a rate of 0.21 mg/hr up to 72 hrs",
    "the total dose up to 24 hrs being 5.46 mg and subsequently 5 mg",
    "At 72 hrs the study was ended",
    "All pulmonary and systemic hemodynamic variables were measured at baseline and at 1, 3, 6, 12, 24, 48, and 72 hrs",
    "Oxygen consumption index, oxygen delivery index, and intrapulmonary right-to-left shunting were measured at baseline as well as 1, 3, 6, 12, 24, 48, and 72 hrs after",
    "Serum and urine concentration of electrolytes (sodium, potassium), creatinine, and urea were measured at baseline and at 6, 12, 24, 48, and 72 hrs after",
    "Urine volume was measured from -6 to 0 hrs (before treatment), and 0–6, 6–12, 12–24, 24–48, and 48–72 hrs.",
    "Hormonal variables were collected at baseline and at 6, 12, 24, 48, and 72 hrs."
  ],
